This concept is a core element of the training program under the Wildlife Crime Leadership Initiative. It is a mandatory requirement for participants throughout the course to apply leadership skills in practice. This project is designed as a tool for learners to demonstrate leadership capabilities and improve operational efficiency within their respective agencies or organizations.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Notably, the Wildlife Conservation Society (WCS) contributed by developing a key tool used in this project: the 'Challenge Definition Matrix.' This matrix assists learners in identifying the specific focus for organizational change‚Äč
Key Milestones, Concepts, and Events in CWT Change Project Implementation‚Äč

1. Key Milestones‚Äč

2022: The publication year of foundational documents cited in the course, including the CIPD‚Äôs SWOT Analysis guide and the SARA model for wildlife protection by Lemieux et al.‚Äč

Leadership Program Duration: The mandatory timeframe within which your change project must be completed.‚Äč

Project Completion Deadline: The point by which participants must finish collecting evaluation data to assess their own effectiveness.‚Äč

12-Day Cycle (e.g., Silky Sharks): A specific biological or operational milestone used to identify peak crime periods based on tidal cycles.‚Äč

Last 6 Months (e.g., Pangolins): The period used to evaluate the effectiveness (or lack thereof) of past law enforcement efforts.‚Äč

2. Core Concepts‚Äč

These concepts form the theoretical and practical framework for the project:‚Äč

CWT Change Project: An initiative aimed at improving the effectiveness of counter-wildlife trafficking efforts within the participant's jurisdiction.‚Äč

Targeting: The first stage in Sherman‚Äôs Triple-T model, focusing on identifying a specific situation that requires improvement.‚Äč

Challenge Definition Matrix: A tool developed by WCS to bridge the gap between individual incidents and systemic organizational challenges.‚Äč

SWOT Analysis: A tool for analyzing internal factors (Strengths, Weaknesses) and external factors (Opportunities, Threats) to select a focal issue.‚Äč

SARA Model: A four-step problem-solving cycle: Scanning, Analysis, Response, and Assessment.‚Äč

Problem Profile & 5W1H: A method for detailed problem definition using six questions: What, Who, Why, How, Where, and When.‚Äč

Communities of Practice (CoPs): Collaboration among individuals with shared interests to exchange ideas and resources, thereby multiplying impact.‚Äč

3. Key Events and Activities‚Äč

Participants are expected to navigate the following stages:‚Äč

Problem Selection: The initial step based on parameters of scope and feasibility.‚Äč

Demonstrating Leadership: Taking charge of a team or proposing new responsibilities to implement the project.‚Äč

Developing a Problem Profile: Drafting a 150-word summary of the chosen challenge.‚Äč

Forum Discussion (Activity 2.3): Posting the profile to receive feedback and connect with peers.‚Äč

Establishing CoPs (Activity 2.4): Seeking out and engaging with those who have similar project ideas to support one another.‚Äč

Effectiveness Evaluation: Conducted at the end of the program to measure the impact of the implemented interventions‚Äč

‚Äč1. Key Parameters‚Äč

These are mandatory requirements that your project must meet:‚Äč

 Feasibility: The project must be capable of completion within the training program's duration so that you can execute the full cycle and evaluate the results.‚Äč

 Demonstrating Leadership: The focus is not on the scale of the project, but on your experience in leading an improvement. You can achieve this through a team you manage or by requesting additional responsibilities from superiors to lead a new initiative.‚Äč

 Objective: To improve a specific issue related to Countering Wildlife Trafficking (CWT) within your jurisdiction.‚Äč

 2. Project Scope‚Äč

The scope determines the scale of the project to ensure feasibility:‚Äč

 Appropriate Size: You should choose a project that is not too large so that evaluation data can be collected before the program concludes.‚Äč

 Small Projects Are Acceptable: If a project is small and completed quickly, you may perform a second cycle to make further improvements.‚Äč

 3. Project Focus: You have two directions for choosing the problem to solve:‚Äč

 Direct: Directly impacting the reduction of wildlife crime (e.g., preventing the poaching of a specific species). ‚Äč

Indirect (Organizational): Addressing internal agency or organizational issues that influence CWT effectiveness (e.g., improving patrol procedures, staff skill training, or better budget management).‚Äč

Decision Support Tools:‚Äč

Tools such as the Challenge Definition Matrix can be used to find links between individual incidents and systemic issues, or a SWOT analysis to identify organizational strengths and weaknesses before starting‚Äč
In the evidence-based approach, the Targeting stage is the first and most crucial step in Sherman's Triple-T model. Below is a brief explanation:‚Äč

Concept: Targeting is the precise identification of the specific situation or problem you aim to improve. Instead of spreading resources thin, you select a focal point to concentrate your efforts.‚Äč

Purpose: It helps clearly define the project scope (CWT change project) and ensures that your efforts yield practical results in countering wildlife trafficking.‚Äč

Support Tools: You can use the Challenge Definition Matrix (to determine whether the issue is an isolated incident or systemic) or a SWOT analysis (to identify weaknesses or opportunities to target).‚Äč

