SWOT is a tool that helps you identify the core issues for your change project by analyzing your organization's internal and external factors.‚Äč

 S (Strengths): Tasks or areas where your agency or team excels.‚Äč

 W (Weaknesses): Areas where your agency or team underperforms or lacks proficiency.‚Äč

 O (Opportunities): Emerging external situations or factors that can support anti-wildlife trafficking efforts.‚Äč

 T (Threats): New threats to wildlife that are currently unaddressed or under-researched.‚Äč

 Practical Examples for Strategic Focus:‚Äč

You can choose to focus your project on one of these four directions:‚Äč

 Focusing on Strengths: If your unit excels at problem-solving analysis for law enforcement strategies, you could develop a project to support other units in analyzing their own wildlife trafficking issues.‚Äč

 Focusing on Weaknesses: If your team underperforms due to a skill gap, you can design a specialized training package to enhance their capabilities.‚Äč

 Focusing on Opportunities: If a new law has recently come into effect but remains under-publicized, you can launch a communication campaign to encourage offenders to cease wildlife crime. ‚Äč

Focusing on Threats: If a new threat emerges against a specific species that has been overlooked, you can begin data collection and analysis to build a future response strategy.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Benefits and Implementation: ‚Äč

Benefits: Helps you make strategic choices and prioritize activities aligned with your organization‚Äôs goals and values.‚Äč

Effective Implementation: This should be a collaborative process to gain diverse perspectives and leverage existing expertise. Avoid getting bogged down in excessive detail; instead, focus on analyzing the essence of the problem.‚Äč

Next Step: After using SWOT to select the issue, the next recommended step is applying the SARA model (Scanning, Analysis, Response, Assessment) to implement the project.‚Äč

‚Äč

The following tips for conducting an effective SWOT analysis are drawn from CIPD (Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development, the oldest professional association in the world in the field of human resource management, headquartered in London, England, established since 1913) resources. These recommendations will help you perform a professional and practical SWOT analysis to identify key issues for your project:‚Äč

Collaborate: Do not perform a SWOT analysis in isolation. Involving multiple stakeholders will provide diverse perspectives and lead to better outcomes.‚Äč

Leverage existing expertise: Utilize the knowledge and resources already available within your organization.‚Äč

Integrate with other tools: Combine SWOT with other techniques (such as PESTLE) to gain a deeper understanding of the operating environment.‚Äč

Make it an ongoing process: Do not treat SWOT as a one-off task; integrate it into a continuous process to monitor ongoing changes.‚Äč

Avoid getting bogged down in detail: Do not collect excessive trivial information; focus on analyzing the core nature of the issues.‚Äč

Avoid jumping to conclusions: Refrain from basing future conclusions solely on past or present events.‚Äč
The SARA model (Scanning, Analysis, Response, and Assessment) was developed in 1987 by criminologists John Eck and William Spelman in collaboration with the Newport News Police Department (Virginia, USA). It serves as a practical framework for Professor Herman Goldstein‚Äôs theory of 'Problem-Oriented Policing' (POP). This model enables law enforcement to shift from reactive responses to proactive problem-solving by addressing the root causes of crime through four systematic steps: scanning the problem, in-depth analysis, implementing responses, and final assessment of effectiveness.‚Äč

‚Äč

The SARA model is the next step after using tools such as the Problem Definition Matrix or SWOT analysis to identify a problem. This is a four-step process that helps you solve problems in a scientific and systematic way:‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Scanning (Identification):‚Äč

 Explanation: This step helps you identify and prioritize issues, then select one specific problem to address.‚Äč

 Example: You notice that lower-level staff at District XXX failed to investigate illegal meat consumption at restaurants, despite it being reported.‚Äč

 Analysis:‚Äč

 Explanation: Gather and analyze information to understand the factors driving or enabling the problem.‚Äč

 Example: Research reveals the root cause is not staff negligence, but rather a lack of understanding regarding new legal regulations on protection.‚Äč

 Response:‚Äč

Explanation: Implement solutions to mitigate the factors causing the problem. The documentation encourages collaboration with partners to diversify intervention options.‚Äč

Example: You design and implement a specialized training package on the new law to boost subordinates' confidence in law enforcement.‚Äč

Assessment:‚Äč

Explanation: Determine the impact of the implemented solution and share the lessons learned.‚Äč

Example: Following the training, you monitor data over the next six months to see if those agencies have begun prosecuting cases related to the issue.‚Äč

Summary: SARA prevents you from jumping straight to solutions; instead, it forces you to understand 'why' the problem exists (Analysis) and verify if your intervention was truly effective (Assessment). This model is applicable to both criminal cases and internal organizational challenges.‚Äč
The 5W1H Framework: Building a Problem Profile The 5W1H framework (What, Who, Why, How, Where, When) is a tool that helps you build a clear and detailed Problem Profile before implementing a solution.‚Äč

1. The Significance of 5W1H in CWT‚Äč

Instead of describing a problem in general terms, you answer the following six questions to "paint" a complete picture of the challenge:‚Äč

What: Which animal species are being threatened, or what is the specific organizational issue?‚Äč

Who: Who are the offenders, or which staff members are involved in this challenge?‚Äč

Why: What is the motive of the criminals, or why is the organizational challenge occurring?‚Äč

How: By what methods is the crime committed, or how does this challenge affect counter-wildlife trafficking efforts?‚Äč

Where: In which specific locations or "hotspots" is the problem occurring?‚Äč

When: At what specific times, months, or weather/tidal conditions does the issue frequently occur?‚Äč

‚Äč

The Problem Profile is a core tool of Problem-Oriented Policing (POP). It was established in the United States in the late 1970s, with Herman Goldstein laying the foundation to shift the mindset from "reacting to incidents" to "proactively addressing root causes."‚Äč

A Problem Profile is an in-depth analytical document built on intelligence to thoroughly understand a specific crime or disorder issue. It encompasses the following:‚Äč

Trend Analysis: Researching emerging or persistent criminal trends.‚Äč

Risk Identification: Identifying high-risk areas, victims, or offenders.‚Äč

Root Cause Analysis: Analyzing underlying factors rather than merely focusing on isolated incidents.‚Äč

Evidence-Based Recommendations: Proposing solution options based on evidence in collaboration with partner agencies.‚Äč

‚Äč
‚Äč

2. Case Study 1: Criminal Problem Profile (Silky Shark Poaching)‚Äč

What: The illegal killing of silky sharks (a protected species).‚Äč

Who: 20 priority targets, supported by 2 traders, all based in Village XXX.‚Äč

Why: Driven by financial motives and social factors.‚Äč

How: Using "lempara" fishing boats with crews of 7 or more, utilizing 12-foot bamboo harpoons with metal tips.‚Äč

Where: At geographical hotspots within the district.‚Äč

When: Early in the morning, during a 12-day window determined by tidal cycles in specific months of the year.‚Äč

‚Äč
‚Äč

3. Case Study 2: Organizational Challenge Profile (Internal Management)‚Äč

What: Junior officers failing to investigate reports regarding the consumption of pangolin meat.‚Äč

Who: Junior officers of the wildlife conservation agency in District XXX.‚Äč

Why: They are unfamiliar with new legal regulations concerning pangolin protection.‚Äč

How: Received 5 to 10 violation reports but initiated no investigations over the past 6 months.‚Äč

Where: In District XXX.‚Äč

When: Whenever they receive reports of violations.‚Äč

‚Äč

Benefit: Breaking down the problem this way prevents you from rushing into immediate solutions. Instead, it allows you to define the problem accurately to ensure the most targeted response.‚Äč

