Project Focus: Crime vs. Organizational Pathways‚Äč

In a CWT change project, you have two primary "pathways" to choose from. Your choice depends on your role and your capacity to influence wildlife trafficking either directly or indirectly.‚Äč

1. The Crime Pathway (External/Direct)‚Äč

This approach focuses directly on criminal incidents or issues occurring in the field.‚Äč

Characteristics: Concentrates on preventing or reducing specific cases of poaching, transportation, or illegal trade.‚Äč

Example (Silky Shark Poaching): Your project focuses on stopping 20 individuals in Village XXX who frequently use bamboo harpoons to kill silky sharks during early morning hours at local hotspots.‚Äč

‚Äč

2. The Organizational Pathway (Internal/Indirect)‚Äč

This is an indirect approach. Rather than targeting the offenders directly, you address internal issues within your agency to enhance counter-trafficking capabilities.‚Äč

Characteristics: Tackles internal barriers such as budget constraints, skill gaps, outdated workflows, or information deficits. Addressing organizational issues has a significant, albeit indirect, impact on reducing field-level crime.‚Äč

Example (Legal Awareness Gap): Your project focuses on resolving the failure of junior officers in District XXX to prosecute pangolin meat consumption cases because they lack knowledge of new laws. The solution might involve developing an internal training package.‚Äč

The Link Between Both Pathways‚Äč

To better understand how to choose, consider the Challenge Definition Matrix:‚Äč

Crime (Boxes 1 & 3): What is happening to the wildlife (e.g., rhinos being killed by organized crime syndicates).‚Äč

Organizational (Boxes 2 & 4): Why your agency has not yet prevented it (e.g., patrol teams lack rations because the budget is spread too thin without focus).‚Äč

If your role does not allow for a direct impact on crime (Pathway 1), you can opt for the Organizational Pathway (Pathway 2). A project that improves intelligence-led patrol planning (an organizational issue) will ultimately help save more snow leopards in the future (a crime issue).‚Äč
