The concept of "Multiplying Impact" through Communities of Practice (CoPs) in Counter Wildlife Trafficking (CWT) change projects is defined as leveraging the power of collaboration among individuals who share common goals or face similar challenges.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

1. What are Communities of Practice?‚Äč

These are groups where people performing the same type of work across different locations share their progress, ideas, and resources with one another.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

2. How does this approach "Multiply Impact"?‚Äč

Building and participating in these communities generates a greater impact than working in isolation by:‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Saving time: Instead of starting from scratch, sharing resources helps everyone complete projects faster.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Avoiding mistakes: Learning from others' experiences ensures you do not repeat the errors they have already encountered.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Improving outcomes: Contributions from diverse perspectives enhance the quality and effectiveness of intervention solutions.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

3. Implementation in the CWT Program‚Äč

The guidelines provide specific steps to foster these connections:‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Identifying peers: After writing a Problem Profile, post it on the discussion forum to find fellow participants with similar ideas or challenges.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Active engagement: Do not hesitate to ask questions of those with similar ideas to deepen your own understanding of the chosen issue.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

Unlimited sharing: Having multiple people choose the same problem is not an obstacle; rather, it is an excellent opportunity to share resources and advance together.‚Äč

 ‚Äč

In summary: "Multiplying impact" through CoPs transforms individual efforts into a collective knowledge network, ensuring your change project achieves optimal and sustainable results‚Äč
